    "recap_headline": "Baylor",
    "recap_text": "WACO, Texas \u2013\nBaylor baseball fell to No. 24 Kansas State, 13-3, in seven innings on Tuesday night at Magnolia Field at Baylor Ballpark in Waco.\nSeven of K-State's (16-5, 2-1 Big 12) nine hits on the night went for extra bases, including four home runs, to help the Wildcats to the run-rule victory. For BU, junior infielder\nRobert De La Garza\nrecorded three hits in three at-bats, while freshman outfielder\nBrady Janusek\nhad two hits and two RBIs on the night.\nOn the mound, senior right-hander\nGrayson Murry\nwas a bright spot with two scoreless innings and matched his career high with three strikeouts. However, four other Bears pitchers combined to allow five walks, each of which eventually scored for KSU.\nTHE RUNDOWN\nK-State got the scoring started with a solo home run and two-run homer in the top of the second to take an early lead. An RBI groundout by junior catcher\nJJ Kennett\ngot Baylor on the board in the bottom half to make it 3-1 after two complete.\nThe Wildcats went deep again in the top of the third, this time a three-run shot that increased the lead to 6-1. Murry took over in the fourth and retired all six batters he faced in order across two scoreless frames, including three strikeouts, to keep the Bears within striking distance.\nDe La Garza led off the bottom of the fifth with a single, but was erased on a double play one batter later. A pair of two-out knocks by sophomore infielder\nCade Dodson\nand redshirt freshman infielder\nBrytton Clements\npreceded a walk to fifth-year senior outfielder\nTy Johnson\n, loading the bases for Janusek who lasered a line drive down the left-field line that chased in two runs. Johnson was thrown out at the plate on a perfect relay from KSU to end the inning, though BU cut into the deficit at 6-3.\nAfter a scoreless sixth, K-State broke it open with two outs in the top of the seventh, exploding for seven runs on five hits and two walks. An RBI single, bases-loaded walk, bases-clearing double and solo home run put the Wildcats ahead by 10 and enacted the run-rule after the Bears went quietly in the home half.\nHIGHLIGHTS\n\u2022 Baylor finished its season-long eight-game homestand with a 5-3 record.\n\u2022 Tonight's game marked BU's ninth this season against a ranked opponent, the most in a single-season by March 17 since 2014.\n\u2022 This was Baylor's first game against a Big 12 opponent in a non-conference game since facing Oklahoma at the 2021 Round Rock Classic.\n\u2022 BU turned its Big 12-leading 21\nst\ndouble play of the season.\n\u2022 Freshman OF\nBrady Janusek\nrecorded his eighth multi-hit and third multi-RBI game of the year, tying a season-high with three hits.\n\u2022 Junior INF\nRobert De La Garza\nnotched a career-high three hits for his third multi-hit performance of the season.\n\u2022 Senior RHP\nGrayson Murry\nset a season high and matched his career high with three strikeouts.\n\u2022 Murry worked his fifth scoreless appearance of the 2026 campaign.\nSTAT OF THE DAY\n3 \u2013 Junior infielder\nRobert De La Garza\nnotched a career-high three hits, and senior right-handed pitcher\nGrayson Murry\nmatched his career high with three strikeouts.\nQUOTABLE\nHead Coach\nMitch Thompson\nOn\nRobert De La Garza's\nperformance\u2026\n\"He's been good. I'm proud of him. I'm proud of the way he's gone about his business. You know, he sat there for a while and waited his turn, and when he got his chance, he stepped in the lineup, and he performed, and he's squaring balls up. He's taking good swings, he's having good at bats. And so, good for him. That's how you get to stay in the lineup and keep getting to swing, so good for him.\"\nWHAT'S NEXT\nBaylor (11-9, 1-2) heads to Stillwater, Okla., for a three-game set against Oklahoma State (13-7, 0-3). The series begins on Friday, March 20, at 6 p.m. from O'Brate Stadium in Stillwater.\nTo stay up to date on all things Baylor baseball, follow the team on its official Facebook, Twitter and Instagram accounts: @BaylorBaseball.\n-BaylorBears.com-"
